Cell["\<\
Notice that in the harmonic oscillator, all of the energy levels are equally \
spaced, and the energy difference between any two adjacent energy levels is\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8095118647113113`*^9, 
  3.8095119021931143`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"25d29650-6a38-4a74-9d0a-\
6581b0a4193d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]", 
    StyleBox["E",
     FontSlant->"Italic"]}]], "=", 
  StyleBox[
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["h",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Nu]"}]]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.80951191180881*^9, 
  3.809511921879463*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"36c572d1-6e70-41a7-95c3-\
ebcc79717849"],

Cell["\<\
The harmonic oscillator turns out to be a very useful when we are dealing \
with molecular vibrations. That\[CloseCurlyQuote]s because it roughly \
approximates the shape of the potential between atoms near the equilibrium \
internuclear distance. We can solve it exactly (which is handy for doing \
further calculations of things like vibrational entropy), and we can use it \
to easily find the many vibrations in a molecule.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.915798144233514*^9, 
  3.9157981932951603`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a97340ca-4551-4fc1-9c97-\
329f14f1f9bb"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Rotation and Angular Momentum", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810052486927634*^9, 3.810052493632394*^9}, {
  3.810052560313609*^9, 3.8100525685622215`*^9}, {3.8101124397541523`*^9, 
  3.810112441609745*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ee358a73-75b0-4479-919d-\
762e744a21bb"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction to the Rigid Rotor", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810052576967537*^9, 3.8100525801214046`*^9}, {
  3.810054150166128*^9, 
  3.810054158945711*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"06e42726-7292-44ca-bd38-\
4a03e12b5968"],

Cell["\<\
We can visualize the simultaneous rotation and vibration of a rotating spring \
with masses on each end, as shown in Figure 5.4. Later, we will apply this \
idea to a diatomic molecule.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100525850843453`*^9, 3.8100526509922247`*^9}, {
  3.810053948166459*^9, 3.8100540482566385`*^9}, {3.841416209305584*^9, 
  3.8414162138549557`*^9}, {3.915800255895078*^9, 
  3.9158002831440334`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"931ce046-cfbb-4d61-bb9d-\
9927730980f2"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

