}, {2}]],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 5.4",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Simultaneous vibration and rotation of a spring connecting two masses, \
Cleonis, Wikipedia, 2006, CC-BY-SA 2.5, \
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ec/Rotational_vibrational_\
coupling.gif"
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.809435027311596*^9, 3.8094350763900714`*^9}, {
  3.80943583474421*^9, 3.8094358359299717`*^9}, {3.8094472165104203`*^9, 
  3.809447281165168*^9}, {3.810054221304062*^9, 3.8100542409148703`*^9}, {
  3.9158002152881627`*^9, 
  3.915800225641918*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"756bde26-a5a2-432b-975b-\
fa2eedd7163f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In reality, rotation and vibration are ",
 StyleBox["coupled",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", which means that they",
 " do influence one another, but we can greatly simplify the motions by \
approximating that they are separate. In this case, we have a rigid rotor, \
that is, two masses connected at a fixed distance. This approach turns out to \
work quite well for the explanation of molecular rotation."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100540492949204`*^9, 3.8100541381633782`*^9}, {
  3.8101084849026165`*^9, 3.81010848557436*^9}, {3.841416257319813*^9, 
  3.8414162581996202`*^9}, {3.9161621978934946`*^9, 
  3.9161622144234343`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e305be3d-42e8-4e92-aa61-\
87c88b9b711f"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Vector Review", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810052576967537*^9, 3.8100525801214046`*^9}, {
  3.810054150166128*^9, 3.810054158945711*^9}, {3.8100542525662117`*^9, 
  3.810054255523529*^9}, {3.8101111353401203`*^9, 
  3.8101111375137005`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"47a357f7-4889-4cca-9fa8-\
556efea8117d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Vectors are extremely useful when discussing rotation and angular momentum, \
so let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s take a moment to review some topics. If you think \
back to your classical mechanics course, you may remember that a vector has \
both magnitude and direction. We usually write a vector symbol in bold, such \
as velocity",
 StyleBox[" ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 StyleBox["v",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and its corresponding scalar symbol (magnitude only) is written only in \
italics, such as speed ",
 StyleBox["v",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". The relation between a vector and its scalar is written mathematically as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100542590946627`*^9, 
  3.8100544257506847`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d430add8-cff8-460c-9f41-\
0b0c11d82b3c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox["v",
   FontSlant->"Italic"], 
  StyleBox["=",
   FontSlant->"Plain"], 
  RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
   StyleBox["v",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810054442023225*^9, 3.810054515137878*^9}, {
  3.915800368750865*^9, 
  3.915800369677005*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2dc389bf-b334-4a16-a9b4-\
a01098480a50"],

Cell["\<\
where we have used the example of speed and velocity, and the brackets \
indicate to take the magnitude of the vector.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810054519804057*^9, 
  3.8100545632312255`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2fac9310-5032-4e84-a550-\
b552daa02a15"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "There are two prominent operations that are unique to vectors. The first is \
known as the scalar product or dot product. For two vectors ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["b",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", it is defined as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100545662933483`*^9, 3.8100546261889477`*^9}, {
  3.8100546846594896`*^9, 3.810054685870128*^9}, {3.915800389155363*^9, 
  3.9158003918768816`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"951814f8-6901-445b-acdd-\
7d5acfbc4d75"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["a",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[CenterDot]", 
   StyleBox["b",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    StyleBox["a",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    StyleBox["b",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "cos", 
   RowBox[{"(", "\[Theta]", ")"}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100544880652375`*^9, 3.8100545041200957`*^9}, {
  3.810054632482561*^9, 3.8100546606919527`*^9}, {3.9158003940787277`*^9, 
  3.915800402288131*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9f801fff-2635-4e25-b3c0-\
6e88310d057d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where \[Theta] is the angle between ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["b",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". As the name implies, the scalar product does not yield a vector but \
rather a scalar (magnitude without direction)."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810054664569395*^9, 3.8100547040855045`*^9}, {
  3.810108534480445*^9, 3.810108547196104*^9}, {3.9158004056346116`*^9, 
  3.9158004085409527`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"962d9965-04f3-45f0-a676-\
ebe6694c0ea7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The other important vector operation is the vector product or cross \
product. For two vectors ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["b",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", it is defined as"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100547065405493`*^9, 3.8100547285730405`*^9}, {
  3.9158004259219947`*^9, 
  3.915800428435789*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a4da5b51-4c58-4170-b6d6-\
7fd6a08e3af4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["a",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Cross]", 
   StyleBox["b",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    StyleBox["a",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
   RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
    StyleBox["b",
     FontWeight->"Bold",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
   StyleBox["c",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   StyleBox[" ",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], "sin", 
   RowBox[{"(", "\[Theta]", ")"}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8100544880652375`*^9, 3.8100545041200957`*^9}, {
  3.810054632482561*^9, 3.8100546606919527`*^9}, {3.810054738405748*^9, 
  3.810054754160844*^9}, {3.915800432502139*^9, 
  3.9158004381766605`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"978ed5fc-0a60-4e49-80e8-\
27b9c3609f5a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is a unit vector (vector of magnitude 1) that is perpendicular to the \
plane formed by ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and ",
 StyleBox["b",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". The direction of ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is given by the right-hand rule, which says that if you curl your fingers \
from ",
 StyleBox["a",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " to ",
 StyleBox["b",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", then ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " will point along the direction of your thumb, as shown in Figure 5.5."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.810054825682743*^9, 3.8100548587706275`*^9}, {
  3.8100548980218744`*^9, 3.810054959085287*^9}, {3.810055012823363*^9, 
  3.8100550184378815`*^9}, {3.8101085600733013`*^9, 3.8101085605117826`*^9}, {
  3.9158004531896544`*^9, 
  3.915800480618853*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"08d3eecd-a582-4700-b008-\
6ce5b97750e1"],

